¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Why} ⦉

  ‖ We view matrix-vector multiplication as a function mapping
    vectors to vectors. ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Result} ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ Define $f: 𝗥^n → 𝗥^m$ by $f(x) = Ax$ where $A ∈ 𝗥^{m ×
    n}$. ⦉

  ‖ We call $f$ the ❬matrix multiplication function❭ associated
    with $A$. ⦉

  ‖ It is easy to verify that $f$ is a linear function. ⦉

  ‖ The converse is true. ⦉

  ‖ \begin{proposition} ⦉

  ‖ Let $f: 𝗥^n → 𝗥^m$ be linear. Then there exists a unique
    $A ∈ 𝗥^{m × n}$ satisfying $f(x) = Ax$ for all $x ∈ 𝗥^n$. ⦉

  ‖ \end{proposition} ⦉

  ‖ \begin{proof} ⦉

  ‖ Evaluate $f$ at the standard basis vectors $e_i$. ⦉

  ‖ The $i$th component of $e_i$ is 1 and all other components
    are 0. ⦉

  ‖ \end{proof} ⦉
⦉

